english:
  title: Stele for the Restoration of Longquan Temple in Daxing County, Great Capital
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the third year of Zhiyuan, on the first day of the fourth month, the Director of Imperial Insignia, Shen, spoke to me saying: "Recently, by command of the Imperial Dowager, I have restored the Buddha Hall of Longquan Temple and purchased fields to be consecrated, so that their yearly yields might furnish oil for the eternal lamp. Through the Buddha's grace, we pray to Heaven for long life and blessings upon the Emperor, the Empress Dowager, the Empress, and the Crown Prince, that all good fortune may gather. I have appointed the Korean Master Gyeongmyeong to oversee this temple. I humbly request that you record its origins and purpose, that future generations might know."

    Having long received kindness from Shen, I could not refuse his request. Thus I set down these words:

    The Buddha's way has flourished under Heaven for ages. In our great Yuan, it is observed with utmost reverence. The Imperial Dowager, we humbly know, has long honored this teaching. Since the passing of the Emperor Wenzong, she has devoted herself even more earnestly to its support, nourishing monks and sustaining the Buddha's work as if each day were insufficient. All great Buddhist undertakings she entrusts to Shen. He stands near the imperial presence, long favored and trusted, and serves the Buddha with unwavering devotion, seeking thus to repay the grace bestowed upon him. Is this not the principle that when those above cherish something, those below embrace it all the more? Though the restoration of this temple is but a small matter, it is surely worthy of record.

    The temple stands in the southern region of Chongyang in Daxing County, some eighty li from the county seat. Its founding age is unknown, though it is said the Master Yuanzhe once restored it. The present Buddha Hall of six bays was erected in the twenty-third year of Dajin. Though destroyed by warfare in the early Yuan, the hall alone survived. Within are images sculpted in the Liu method—the Three Bodies of karmic manifestation, Manjushri and Samantabhadra, the Four Bodhisattvas of Wisdom, and the Avalokiteshvara—thirty-six transformation images in all. Prayers offered here receive swift response. That the hall escaped fire surely testifies to its spiritual power. Master Yuanzhe entered nirvana in the late Taihe period, after which Masters Xiangdeng, Deyin, and Zhigai successively presided. The temple once held six hundred mu of fields; now two hundred mu have been consecrated. Yet such property bred contention among those who love gain.

    In the year of Renshen of Yanyou, those called Xianchen and Xianjin transferred the temple to Master Zhanbandar. When he later returned to the Western Regions, he entrusted its care to Li Xin, Minister of the Central Secretariat, as external patron. Li renovated the abbot's quarters, the monks' cells, and the kitchens, intending to rebuild the hall itself, but circumstances required his departure. He entrusted the work to Shen and to his nephew, Censor Cui Baiyuan. Shen said to Gyeongmyeong, Cui's son: "I once revered Li as a father, and you are his kinsman. Should we restore this temple and place you at its head, we would fulfill Li's noble wish."

    Thereupon, by imperial decree, forty-five thousand bolts of silk cash were donated to accomplish the restoration. At this time, Master Yonggulu, the dharma heir of Zhanbandar, came from the Western Regions to take up residence here. Hearing of Shen's devotion, his heart aligned with theirs, and he contributed eight thousand strings of coins to support the work, asking only that others benefit, claiming nothing for himself.

    Alas! When Master Yuanzhe restored this temple long ago, he gathered the faithful's offerings and the temple's meager stores to ensure its enduring welfare. Yet after his passing, for centuries those dwelling here knew only to quarrel over gain, none taking responsibility for its restoration. How fortunate that men like Li appeared to initiate the work and Shen to sustain it, establishing firm leadership to end the strife, while Master Gyeongmyeong faithfully managed it all, renewing the structures and enriching the resources, so that the lineage continues unbroken and the temple gains lasting support, with the Buddha's work shining anew. This too is worthy of record.

    I have heard that the Buddha takes emptiness as supreme principle and compassion and non-killing as his teaching, saying: "Commit no evil; practice all good." Though this teaching may not directly order the state, should we extend this heart universally so that all people learn to cherish good and abhor evil, ascending to the realm of benevolence and longevity, would this not be no small blessing? This is why the Buddha's way endures throughout Heaven and Earth. Let this be inscribed.

    The inscription reads:

    Ancient kings established teaching,
    In the middle way alone.
    Ritual guides, punishment spurs—
    No darkness remains unenlightened.
    The Buddha's doctrine claims:
    Mystery dwells in emptiness.
    Through compassion all are transformed;
    Few refuse to follow.
    Through Han and Tang ages,
    The teaching grew ever richer.
    When the Yuan arose,
    Both faith and reverence deepened.
    Pagodas and temples stretch across the land;
    Barbarian and Chinese walk as one.
    On Yan's sunny heights,
    East of Yi's waters,
    A precious temple faces ruin,
    Its monks grieve in sorrow.
    The Imperial Dowager,
    Long devoted to the Buddha's way,
    Opened the inner treasury,
    Building anew.
    Who undertook this deed?
    Shen, in truth.
    In the palace's inner circle,
    He stands with reverence and loyalty,
    Once serving the late Emperor,
    Favored by the imperial consort.
    Heaven and Earth's vast creation—
    I bow before such greatness.
    May we rely on the Buddha's inconceivable way
    To express our humble hearts,
    Aiding the Great Plan,
    That all endure with Heaven and Earth.
    These words are carved in stone,
    Their truth passed to ages unborn.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhiyuan (至元) was the era name of Kublai Khan (r. 1260-1294), placing this stele in 1277.
  - key: ''
    value: The Imperial Dowager (太皇太后) refers to Kublai Khan's mother, Sorghaghtani Beki, though the text may refer to a later imperial dowager given the reference to Emperor Wenzong.
  - key: ''
    value: Dajin refers to the Jin Dynasty (1115-1234); the twenty-third year of Dajin would be 1243.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Liu method' (劉氏塑法) refers to a particular sculptural technique, likely named after a renowned Buddhist sculptor.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Three Bodies (三身) represent three aspects of Buddha: the Dharma Body (法身), the Enjoyment Body (報身), and the Emanation Body (化身).'
